-EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I could offer the official answer of the Roman Catholic church and say it happens during the Mass when the priest calls upon God during the consecration of the Eucharist.  Also, it is said that it must be a priest and not a layman who does this.  Basically, only someone who can say a Mass.  It is God who actually does the action though.<br>
<br>
This is where I'm not exactly sure what I beleive.  I really do believe in the Eucharist being the body and blood, but I'm not sure that I agree that only a priest can call upon God for the action to take place.  I have wondered when partaking of communion in a church that considers it symbolic only that if I believe that God can transform the element...  would He do so?<br>
<br>
There's a thought that can keep me awake at nights. <p>Christians know that it is not possible to reject or ignore God without demeaning man<br>
- John Paul II at WYD 2002<br>
<br>
